'''Allan Adamson Black''' (1832–4 December 1865) was a Scottish botanist. He was the first curator of [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Kew]] Herbarium (1853–1864)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kewguild.org.uk/media/pdfs/v1s3p1-27.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-09-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045839/http://www.kewguild.org.uk/media/pdfs/v1s3p1-27.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-04 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> and a superintendent of the Lal Bagh botanic garden at Bangalore. He died on ship, H.M.S. Dalhousie, off the Cocos Islands on 4 December 1865. He was the fourth son of Reverend John Black of Perthshire.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Greenock Telegraph and Clyde Shipping Gazette|date=23 January 1866|page=3|title=Death|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000472/18660123/006/0003|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]}}</ref>

