{{Other uses}}

A '''coronach''' (also written '''coranich''', '''corrinoch''', '''coranach''', '''cronach''', etc.) is the Scottish Gaelic equivalent of the Goll,<ref>{{cite book|last=Purser|first=John|title=Scotland's Music|year=1981|publisher=Mainstream|pages=296–7}}</ref> being the third part of a round of [[keening]], the traditional improvised singing at a death, wake or funeral in the [[Highlands of Scotland]] and in [[Ireland]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Ó Madagáin|first=Breandán|title=Caointe agus Seancheolta Eile / Keening and other old Irish music|year=2005|publisher=Cló Iar-Chonnachta|pages=14 & 84}}</ref> Though observers have reported hearing such songs in Ireland or in the Scottish Highlands, and melodies have been noted down and printed since the 18th century, audio recordings are rare; not only was the practice dying out or being suppressed through the 19th century, but it was also considered by its practitioners to have been a very personal and spiritual practice, not suitable for performance or recording.

The Scottish border ballad ''[[The Bonny Earl of Murray]]'' is supposedly composed in the tradition of the coronach.

[[Schubert]]'s Opus 52 No 4 (D 836) set words from [[Sir Walter Scott]]'s ''[[Lady of the Lake]]'' under the title ''Coronach'', for female choir with piano accompaniment. 

==In popular culture==
*[[Progressive rock]] group [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]] released, with [[Dee_Palmer|David Palmer]], a single called "Coronach" in 1986. The single was used as the theme tune to the [[Channel 4]] programme "The Blood Of The British".
*[[Melodic death metal]] band [[Eternal Tears of Sorrow]] have a song entitled "Coronach" on their 1998 album, ''[[Vilda Mánnu]]''.
*[[Death metal]] band [[Hate Eternal]] have an instrumental song entitled "Coronach" as the last song on their 2008 album, ''Fury and Flames''. (The album as a whole is dedicated to [[Jared Anderson (heavy metal musician)|Jared Anderson]], a deceased friend and former bandmate of band leader [[Erik Rutan]].)

