The '''Life Cairn''' is a type of public [[memorial]] built around the world for species rendered extinct by human activity. It takes the form of a [[cairn]].<ref>Symington, Martin (2011). ''Sacred Britain, A Guide to places to Stir the Soul'', p. 28. Bradt Travel Guides, London. {{ISBN|978-1841623634}}.</ref> The first Life Cairn was raised on [[Mount Caburn]], near [[Lewes]] in East Sussex.  The inaugural opening ceremony was held on 22 May 2011.  A Life Cairn was dedicated to [[Lonesome George]] at the [[Galapagos National Park]] on July 26, 2012 and an additional Life Cairn is being raised in Stockholm.

The Life Cairn memorial programme was started by BBC TV presenter Reverend [[Peter Owen Jones]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.resurgence.org/magazine/article3629-life-cairn-ii.html|title=Resurgence • Article - Life Cairn II|work=resurgence.org}}</ref> known for his TV series ''[[Around the World in 80 Faiths]]'' and Andreas Kornevall, the Director for the environmental charity, the Earth Restoration Service (Registered Charity No. 1118951).<ref>{{cite web|title=Who we are|url=http://www.earthrestorationservice.org/about-ers/who-we-are-2/|publisher=Earth Restoration Service|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{EW charity | num=1118951 | name=Earth Restoration Service | accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>

