{{article issues| {{Original research|date=February 2018}} {{Example farm|reason=How many of these are actually called "swamp monsters" in scholarly literature, and how many are creatures from folklore that are in some wayassociated with swamps (or lakes or rivers) that a Wikipedian decided to call "swamp monsters"? Without sources, we can't tell.|date=February 2018}} }} A '''swamp monster''' (also variously called a '''swamp creature''', '''swamp man''', or '''muck monster''')<ref>Jon B. Cooke and George Khoury, ''Swampmen: Muck-Monsters and their Makers'' (2015), p. 6, {{ISBN|1605490571}}.</ref> is a fictional creature found imagined to lurk in a [[swamp]].
Legends of swamp creatures, passed on from generation to generation, are usually bound to a specific swamp.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}
==Swamp monsters in folklore, legends, and mythology== *The [[Will-o'-the-wisp]] appears in swamps, and in some areas there are legends of it being an evil spirit.<ref>Observations on Popular Antiquities: Including the Whole of Mr. Bourne's Antiquitates Vulgares (1777).</ref> *The [[Bunyip]] are a creature from [[Aboriginal mythology]] that lurk in swamps, billabongs, creeks, riverbeds, and waterholes. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://pickle.nine.com.au/2017/08/04/11/30/expedia-map-mythical-creatures-around-world-bunyips-drop-bears-australia|title=Expedia produces map of the world's mythical creatures and, yes, drop bears made the cut|website=pickle.nine.com.au}}</ref> *The [[Grootslang]] are huge elephant-like creature with a serpent's tail which according to legend live in caves, swamps, freshwater in South Africa. <ref>[[Giants, Monsters & Dragons]]: An Encyclopedia of Folklore, Legend, and Myth By Carol Rose</ref> *The [[Lernaean Hydra]] in [[Greek mythology|Greek]] and [[Roman mythology]], was the creature [[Heracles]] killed in the swamp near [[Lerna|Lake Lerna]].<ref>H. David Brumble, ''Classical Myths and Legends in the Middle Ages and Renaissance: A Dictionary of Allegorical Meanings'' (1998), p. 156.</ref> *The [[Honey Island Swamp monster]] in Louisiana.<ref name="Bane"/><ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://www.animalplanet.com/tv-shows/lost-tapes/creatures/swamp-creature/|title=Swamp Creature|date=13 August 2012|publisher=}}</ref> <ref name="Bane">Theresa Bane, ''Encyclopedia of Beasts and Monsters in Myth, Legend and Folklore'' (2016), p. 211.</ref> *[[Mokele-mbembe]], a legendary water-dwelling creature of Congo River basin folklore. <ref>{{cite book|last=Coleman|first=Loren|title=The Field Guide to Lake Monsters, Sea Serpents, and Other Mystery Denizens of the Deep|publisher=Jeremy P. Tarcher|location=New York|year=2003|isbn = 978-1-58542-252-4|ref={{harvid|Coleman|2003}}}}</ref> *The [[skunk ape]] is a horrible smelling large ape creature said to live in swamps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/62786.stm|title=BBC News - Americas - The abominable swampman|website=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> *The [[Lizard Man of Scape Ore Swamp]] <ref name=washpo1>The Washington Post (1988-08-14) "'Lizard Man' Claims a Casualty", The Washington Post</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3188604/Is-South-Carolina-s-Lizard-Man-New-images-claim-mythic-swamp-monster-prankster-lizard-costume.html|title=New images claim to show mythic Lizard Man monster|publisher=|date=2015-08-07}}</ref>
==Examples in comics== [[File:AirboyJune1952.jpg|thumb|The [[Heap (comics)|Heap]] in mortal combat with the "Man of the Moonlight" on the cover of ''[[Airboy|Airboy Comics]],'' vol. 9 #5 (June 1952). Artwork by Ernest Schroeder.]]From the 1940s to the present many swamp monsters have been used in comics, an early example being Hillman Publications' the [[Heap (comics)|Heap]].
Afterwards, both [[DC Comics]] and [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] created similar characters: * DC had the [[Swamp Thing]], created by [[Len Wein]] and [[Berni Wrightson]]. * Marvel had the [[Man-Thing]], created by [[Stan Lee]], [[Gray Morrow]], [[Roy Thomas]], and [[Gerry Conway]].
The debuts of the two characters were so close that it is impossible to say which came first.<ref>{{cite book| last = Cotter| first = Robert Michael "Bobb"| title = The Great Monster Magazines: A Critical Study of the Black and White Publications of the 1950s, 1960s and 1970s| year = 2008| publisher = McFarland| location = Jefferson, North Carolina| isbn = 978-0-7864-3389-6| page = 80 }}</ref> [[Alan Moore]], who worked on ''Swamp Thing'' for a period, later described the character's original incarnation as "a regurgitation of Hillman Comics' The Heap", adding that "When I took over that character at Len Wein's suggestion, I did my best to make it an original character that didn't owe a huge debt to previously existing swamp monsters."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seraphemera.org/seraphemera_books/AlanMoore_Page5.html|title=Interview with Alan Moore Page 5 of 8 |publisher=Seraphemera|date=February 19, 2013}}</ref>
Other swamp monsters in comics include: * [[Solomon Grundy (comics)|Solomon Grundy]], created by [[Alfred Bester]] and [[Paul Reinman]] for DC Comics * The [[Glob (comics)|Glob]], created by [[Roy Thomas]] and [[Herb Trimpe]] for Marvel Comics * Swamp Beast, from ''[[Monster in My Pocket]]'' by [[Dwayne McDuffie]] and [[Gil Kane]] for [[Harvey Comics]]. * [[Bog Swamp Demon]], a fictional character appearing in ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'' comic books. * [[Danny Dunn and the Swamp Monster]] by [[Raymond Abrashkin]] and [[Jay Williams (author)|Jay Williams]]. * In the anime and manga ''[[Princess Resurrection]]'', the characters are attacked by a tribe of monsters resembling the creature while vacationing by a lagoon, who desire Hime's blood to make them immortal and keep their kind from dying out. In a possible reference to the novel version of the movie, one of the creatures is roughly 30 feet tall. {{issue|date=February 2018}} * In the anime and manga ''[[One Piece]]'', the crew is attacked by Caribou who has eaten the Swamp Swamp Fruit (a Logia-type Devil Fruit that lets it's consumer turn into a "swamp").{{issue|date=February 2018}}
==Examples in other media== * The title creature in [[Theodore Sturgeon]]'s 1940 short story "[[It! (short story)|It!]]" is the earliest example of a plant-based swamp monster. * The [[Gill-man]] from the 1954 film ''[[Creature from the Black Lagoon]]'' appears as a fish-like humanoid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.virginia.edu/content/take-look-inside-uva-employee-matthew-gattos-parlor-horrors|title=Take a Look Inside UVA Employee Matthew Gatto's 'Parlor of Horrors'|date=24 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref> ** A creature, credited as the Gill-man, also appears in the non-Universal release ''[[The Monster Squad]]'' (1987) along with [[Count Dracula]], [[Frankenstein's monster|Frankenstein's Monster]], the [[Mummy (undead)|mummy]], and the [[The Wolf Man (1941 film)|Wolf Man]]. He was portrayed by [[Tom Woodruff, Jr.]] * An episode of ''[[Kolchak: The Night Stalker]]'' entitled "The Spanish Moss Murders" (December 6, 1974) features a young man, subject of a study in sleep research, whose nightmares of a [[Spanish moss]]-covered swamp-dwelling monster called ''Pèremalfait'' from stories heard in his youth in the Louisiana Bayou come to life. (The creature in this case was played by [[Richard Kiel]].) * The DC comics character "Swamp Thing" mentioned above was the subject of [[Swamp Thing (film)|a 1982 film]] and [[Swamp Thing (TV series)|a 1990 live-action television series]]. * In the 1986 novel ''[[It (novel)|It]]'' by [[Stephen King]], It takes the form of a swamp monster to kill Eddie Corcoran. * The 1996 ''[[Goosebumps]]'' book "How to Kill a Monster" featured a Swamp Monster. It was depicted as a green-furred monster with the head of an alligator and a gorilla-like body. ** The Swamp Monster makes an appearance in the 2015 ''[[Goosebumps (film)|Goosebumps]]'' movie performed by Nate Andrade (who was credited as "Monster #1"). He is one of Slappy the Dummy's monster and villain henchmen and is referred to as the "Bog Monster" during the 2014 [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic Con]] appearance. Its appearance is different where it looks like a giant creature made of moss. * The TV series ''[[Family Guy]]'' featured some swamp monsters. In the episode "[[I Never Met the Dead Man]]" (April 11, 1999), the Griffin family catches a creature strongly resembling a "Swamp Monster" while fishing. In the episode "[[Business Guy]]" (December 13, 2009), [[Carter Pewterschmidt]] and [[Lois Griffin]] trick [[Peter Griffin]] into surrendering Pewterschmidt Industries by scaring him into believing a local swamp monster will eat him if he does not. A seemingly real swamp monster scares Peter out of the office and then chases Lois and a disguised Carter before being trapped and unmasked to be [[Gregory House]]. * Victor Crowley is a deformed killer and main character in [[Adam Green (filmmaker)|Adam Green]]'s 2006 film, ''[[Hatchet (film)|Hatchet]]''. * [[David Winning]]'s 2008 film ''[[Swamp Devil]]'' stars [[Bruce Dern]] as a retired sheriff trying to prove the existence of a swamp monster. * In [[Animal Planet]]'s ''[[Lost Tapes]],'' the episode "Swamp Creature" (January 26, 2009) is about the [[Honey Island Swamp monster|Louisiana Swamp Monster]], which is said to be an abandoned Native American child who was raised by alligators. <ref name="auto"/> * While criticizing a movie featuring a swamp monster, one of the hosts of the 2010 series ''[[This Movie Sucks!]]'' ([[Ron Sparks (comedian)|Ron Sparks]]) tells the legend of ''[[Lake Erie]] Pete'' about a man who becomes a crime-fighting swamp monster after his parents are killed by one. * In the video game ''[[Infamous 2]]'', the Swamp Monsters are the least mutated type of the Corrupted that have scythes instead of forearms and are the more common of the Corrupted. * In [[Scream Queens (season 2)|Season Two]] of ''[[Scream Queens (2015 TV series)|Scream Queens]]'', the Green Meanie is described to be a swamp monster that lives in a toxic swamp near the C.U.R.E. Institute Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.romper.com/p/these-scream-queens-killer-theories-prove-the-green-meanie-could-be-anyone-22595|title=These 'Scream Queens' Killer Theories Prove The Green Meanie Could Be Anyone|first=Megan|last=Walsh|publisher=}}</ref>
